Best Practices for Writing a switch Statement in Java
=====================================================
Use switch when comparing a single expression against multiple fixed values.
Ensure each case label contains a unique constant value.
Add a break statement at the end of each case to prevent unintended fall-through.
Omit break only when fall-through is intentional, and add a comment explaining the reason.
Always include a default case to handle unexpected or unsupported values.
Keep each case focused on a single responsibility to improve readability and maintainability.
Group multiple case labels together when they should execute the same logic.
Use meaningful variable names for the expression being evaluated.
Avoid writing complex business logic directly inside case blocks; delegate it to separate
methods when possible.
Remember that once a matching case is found, Java jumps to that location and executes statements 
sequentially until it encounters a break, return, throw, or reaches the end of the switch.
Do not rely on fall-through behavior unless it is a deliberate design choice, as it can make
 the code difficult to understand and maintain.
Prefer the enhanced switch expressions (introduced in newer Java versions) when you need to
 return a value, as they eliminate accidental fall-through and produce cleaner, more concise code.

Key Takeaway

A switch statement performs the comparison only once to identify the matching case. After that,
 it executes statements sequentially from the matched case until it encounters a break, return,
  throw, or the end of the switch block. Therefore, using break appropriately is essential to 
  avoid unintended execution of subsequent cases.